Merge pull request #381 from Affectiva/upstream-fix-sdp-offer-bundle-parsing

fix sdp offer bundle parsing when streaming video-only or audio-only

fix sdp offer bundle parsing when streaming video-only or audio-only

The fix is to simply change the 4 to a 3 so that the conditional code to add the BundleTag objects to the bundleTags vector.  Credit to Jeremy Noring on the lynckia google group for finding this fix.

In the case of video-only `a=group:BUNDLE video` or audio-only `a=group:BUNDLE audio`, the number of parts is only 3.  Without the bundle tags, the remote description had an invalid bundle definition `a=group:BUNDLE`.  Most of the time with WebRTC the bundle definition will be `a=group:BUNDLE audio video` for audio and video streaming.

This fixes video-only and audio-only streaming in Chrome 47.

Update RTP packet queue to be based on time, not packet count

The problem with basing it on packet count is it makes sync between our audio and video tracks difficult because # of packets has nothing to do with the duration of the content. Fix an issue where an erizo agent asserted because uv_close was somehow called repeatedly

Somehow this is being called repeatedly, and resulting in stuff blowing up.  Change it so we check uv_is_closing() before closing out our handles.  If there's a close in progress (or it's already closed--the check works foer both), don't bother closing it.

Do not send FIR frames constantly if we're recording

This is both A) a violation of the WebRTC spec and B) explodes image quality and network bandwidth, particularly for multi-party chat where the coordinated FIR requests decimate network quality on a periodic basis. Preserve candidate ordering

Merge pull request #189 from jnoring/upstream

Add WebRTC's FEC processing to ExternalOutput

Fix deadlock with SdesTransport, clean up locking

WebRtcConnection would deadlock writing to a SdesTransport because it would hold receiveVideoMutex_ while calling into Transport->write(); on SdesTransport, however, it would ultimately call back into WebRtcConnection::queueData, which attempts to hold receiveVideoMutex_.  This causes a deadlock since boost::mutex isn't recursive.

Change this so we don't hold receiveVideoMutex_ when calling into transport->write(); receiveVideoMutex_ now locks only around the queue in WebRtcConnection and does not hold the lock when calling into child classes.

Few more changes:

1. In NiceConnection, remove agentMutex_; I don't see a good reason to protect this object in the NiceConnection.
2. remove spurrious NiceConnection->start() call; no longer does any work.
3. Remove spurrious queue item call in WebRtcConnection.cpp; setting the "bail" variables and firing the condition object works just as well.

Remove the queue packet call in the destructor; that call was doing nothing previously because the state had been set to FINISHED, and no packet is queued in that state.

Change the code so we set running_ to false and ICE_FINISHED, and then signal the condition.  In getPacket(), have code that checks the state and returns appropriately.  This allows the Dtls thread to bail.
Let's stop trying to take locks in destructors.  It's a bad pattern and it implies some other threading problem that needs to be resolved.  The only thing it'll result in is deadlocks.
Remove unused GMainLoop variable.
No need for a recursive mutex.
Remove err.txt, accidentally checked in.

Add WebRTC's FEC processing to ExternalOutput

WebRTC does FEC processing to reduce corruption in video due to packet loss.  Let's implement that!  I stripped out just the FEC portion of WebRTC and incorporated that.  One important note: WebRTC has its own endianness detection that's implemented in rtp_utility.cc; it is very important to get that right or you're find yourself exploding inside std::list in a really confusing way.  I think the routine as-is will work for licode across the board, but we probably want to double-check that.

Recording should be unaffected; the only consequence of this change should be "less corruption" in output video.  Corruption is still possible until ExternalOutput starts receiving retransmitted packets coming in on the Rtx SSRC channel.

Merge pull request #180 from jnoring/master

Some mutex cleanup, fix for a deadlock
Fix a memory leak in DtlsSocket where it was not calling X509_free(). Also remove some unused functions, get rid of C-style variable declaration.

Fix two problems:
1. Local candidates were put into a global variable, which means they could be overwritten and broken by simultanious calls to fetch local candidates.
2. Was not deallocating memory from nice_agent_get_local_candidates

Remove a bunch of unnecessary manual locking.  When using RAII objects (like unique_lock, for example), when the object goes out of scope it automatically unlocks.  So there's no need to do this before a return statement, before going out of scope (e.g. inside a while loop), etc.

Fix to address a deadlock that happens sometimes when ice negotiation fails.  updateIceState fires an event holding stateMutex_, and that causes a lock with the WebRTCConnection class.  Also, clean up some vestigial junk, make locking more granular (we were holding nested locks to check ice state, for example--putting the lock after checking ice state removes that issue), etc.

Add the stream when ice negotiation finishes.

When it takes longer to send the 'ok' message over socket.io than it
takes to move the ice connection into the complete state, we end up
failing to notify everyone else in the room that there is another
stream.

Instead of waiting for the 'ok' message, create the stream when the ice
connection moves into the complete state. This eliminates the race
condition and ensures that a connected stream is always fully published.

The other side effect here is that the 'ok' message is no longer needed.
I left it for compatibility, but it can easily be removed.

Fix so we don't record corrupted frames.

When there's packet loss, there's a possibility that we end up constructing a corrupted frame and hand that to libav.  The resulting corruption is much worse than if we had just skipped the frame entirely.  This change also fixes audio handling (it was incorrectly computing header size) and optimizes it slightly so we're not doing an unnecessary memcpy.

One side affect of this is we have to examine the VP8 header before we copy it into our unpackage buffer.  This also ends up optimizing stuff slightly though.

Also, zap input processor member variable and audio buffer; we don't need either of these anymore.

Two bugfixes:

1. the RED packet handling was incorrectly offsetting into final buffer by the total header length instead of the rtp header length.  in theory this matters a lot; in practice, it worked because the size of the red header doesn't seem to be different from the size of the RTP header (???)
2. Not accounting for RTP packet padding in the recorder; RTP packets can (again, in theory) be padded with stuff after the payload.  Strip that off before we hand it down to the rest of the RTP code so it doesn't have to deal with it.

Several updates to recording:

1. Change the audio queue to be significantly deeper than the video queue.  This is because audio in WebRTC almost always contains 20 msec frames, but video is anywhere from 5 to 30 fps, which is 200 to 33 msec per frame.  With low-framerate streams, old code would cause the RTP packet reordering queue to drop samples.
2. Deeper RTP packet re-ordering.  Bump it to 60.
3. Account for the difference in start time between audio and video streams.  This helps AV stay in sync, particularly with the deeper queue.
4. Do not wait for both queues to be ready before writing.  This allows us A) to create audio only files and B) prevents one stream from preventing the other from recording.

Merge branch 'jnoring-master'

Re-write of RtpPacketQueue.cpp, which was not correctly handling:

1. Out of order data
2. Jumps in data
3. RTP sequence number rollover
4. Maintaining queue depth (it was simply nuking the entire queue any time it grew too large instead of trimming it)

Use of the std::map structure seems like a good choice at first, but it is problematic for the first three issues. a std::list is a better choice, given that A) most inserts are going to be at or near the front of the list, minimizing linear search cost and B) traversing a list of 100 things is trivial anyway.  It's more simple and doesn't have some of the above corner cases.

Also change the dataPacket size to 1500; it's possible to have video packets that are larger than 1200 bytes, particularly for keyframes.

Lastly, change ExternalOutput not to write any data while the audio and video queues have fewer than 15 items in them.  This is to allow a window of time for packet re-ordering to occur.  I want to make this more sophisticated in the near future.

Merge pull request #107 from jnoring/master

A bunch of C++ cleanup; lots of leaks, bad iterator usage, etc.
Rename a variable to make it more clear it's member, fix some leaks in the videomixer code.

Fix some leaks, remove exit() calls, fix incorrect scoped_ptr usage.  Scoped_ptr calls delete under the hood, so using .reset() with malloc will cause both a leak and a memory allocation lib mis-match, resulting in undefined behavior.  Exit calls should never be used inside an application; it causes the entire app to stop running.
Fix a crash that could happen due to unpackagedBuffer_ ptr being incremented; when it was free'd and didn't point to the original location, it blows up. Also fix a few more leaks.

Fix memory leaks, rename variables so it's more clear they're member variables of the class, remove unnecessary memcpy (already happens above--doing it a second time does nothing, unless there's some other thread overwriting that buffer.  If that's the case, a mutex is the appropriate fix, not copying the buffer repeatedly)
Remove a bunch of unnecessary memset that are immediately followed by a memcpy; the memcpy is going to overwrite anything in that memory location, so the memset is pointless.
Fix memory leaks in the srtpSessionKey handling; it was allocating memory that was not being free'd.  Changed it so teh SrtpSessionKeys class handles all allocation and deallocation.
Fix some memory leaks; stuff should begin its life as null always be deleted, and end its life as null.  Also zap unused pointer.
Check for null before deleting.  Also zap some unused stuff.
Fix potential memory leak.
Fix incorrect iterator usage, and update a log message to be correct.  Cannot erase the iterator currently being used; need to assign to return value of erase()
Fix memory leak in the case of an error.
Remove unused variable, commented out code.

Fix some super weird code in the dtls directory; this code is incorrectly freeing something it didn't allocate in the first place, although that would never happen because of an if-check that was wrong.  The memory it should be freeing shoul dbe freed with OPENSSL_free(), not regular free().
Fix unsafe iterator behavior.  Once the iterator is erased, it is invalid and cannot be used.  It needs to be replaced by the iterator returned by erase().
nice_ doesn't need to be initialized anymore since it's a smart pointer.  remove unnecessary "friend" class.
Fix constructor, initialize nice_, remove spurrious semicolons
Release our context when we're done with it, otherwise it'll leak.
iceState and context_ are not initialized in the constructor.  Also move some stuff that's initialized in the constructor manually.
Fix an issue with memory not being cleaned up; according to libnice the string output needs to be cleaned up with g_free()
Reduce the scope of a variable, and remove pointless memsets (the same memory is immediately overwritten by the subsequent memcpy)
Changed threading in NiceConnection and DtlsTransport

NiceConnection is now a shared_ptr in Transports
the NiceConnection is now also dettached from the main loop when
destructing
